	('55800f5a-d2d0-4c88-b112-25dfac1f2fc5','READ','Project','36','{\"Project\":{\"id\":\"36\",\"owner_user_id\":\"2\",\"status_id\":\"6\",\"likelihood_id\":\"2\",\"programme_id\":\"2\",\"title\":\"Upstream Conflict Prevention in Central Asia (UCPCA)\",\"fund_code\":\"\",\"summary\":\"The Ferghana Valley\\u2019s conflict potential has been recognised for many years due to its complicated borders and enclaves, cross-border disputes over resources, violent outburst of inter-ethnic conflict and militant activity. Since 2010 the conflict dynamics has intensified with a significant rise of ethno-nationalism in Kyrgyzstan, a rise in tensions between the secular government and the religious opposition in Tajikistan and alleged growing influence of radical Islamist groups penetrating from Afghanistan. In this context cross-border disputes between Tajikistan and Kyrgyzstan continue (despite nominal progress), mainly over the use of water and land in an area without clearly demarcated borders and often unprofessional and corrupt border police. Many early-warning and conflict prevention programmes have been implemented, but not always sustainably, as many issues do remain unexplored or wrongly perceived. At present a small number of organisations work on conflict prevention in the region with which Alert will coordinate closely (e.g. UNDP, Saferworld working with communities across the border, EFCA working with young people in both countries, Search for Common Ground training youth reporters in south Kyrgyzstan, and OSCE supporting media freedom). The project will build upon previous and on-going work done by Alert: it will be closely linked with an EU-project strengthening\",\"start_date\":\"2012-04-01\",\"finish_date\":\"2015-03-31\",\"value_required\":\"390\",\"value_sourced\":\"389\",\"created\":\"2015-06-16 12:58:18\",\"modified\":\"2015-06-16 12:58:18\",\"deleted\":false},\"Status\":{\"id\":\"6\",\"name\":\"Completed\",\"short_name\":\"completed\",\"sort_order\":\"4\"},\"Li